But to ‘ hear of’ must be understood of lines 23, 24, and it is better to take a sense which will suit both divisions of the stanzas. Page pertinently observes that the addition of the phrase non indecoro pulvere sordidos pre- eludes this interpretation: “it is as absurd to say ‘1 hear great leaders begrimed', &c., as it would be to say ‘ I heard Mr. Gladstone in evening dress '. '' It may be added that generals harangued their troops bessare an action, and that they are pulvere sordidi whether indecoro or non indecoro aster it.
